The `NullPointerException` is caused by:
Add Null Check for cls Variable
Add a null check for the `cls` variable before calling `getSimpleName()` on it. This will prevent the `NullPointerException` from occurring.

```java
if (cls != null) {
    String name = cls.getSimpleName();
    // ...
}
```

Check if cls is a Class
Add a check to ensure that `cls` is a class, not an interface, before trying to get its superclass. This will prevent the `NullPointerException` from occurring.

```java
if (cls.isAssignableFrom(Class.class)) {
    cls = cls.getSuperclass();
    // ...
}
```

Use getDeclaringClass() instead of getSuperclass()
Instead of using `getSuperclass()` to get the superclass of `cls`, use `getDeclaringClass()` to get the class that declares `cls`. This will prevent the `NullPointerException` from occurring.

```java
cls = cls.getDeclaringClass();
// ...
```
